h3. Issue Summary

When accessing a Project main page under 'Issues' there are a number of default filters. There are two filters ('My Open Issues' & 'Open Issues') that utilize JQL that includes the following string:
{code:java}
statusCategory in ("New", "In Progress") {code}
In this JQL 'New' is not a valid status category. There are only 3 valid returns here; To Do, In Progress, Done.

!Status Categories.png|width=217,height=146!

As 'New' is not a valid Status Category the coded JQL should not return this value.  It should be 'To Do'. 
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Access any Project main page
 # Click on 'My Open Issues' or 'Open Issues' quick filter

h3. Expected Results

We would assume the coded JQL would have 'To Do' instead of 'New'.  'New' is not a valid search variable that therefore will not return valid results. 

When leveraging the API, the *status.statusCategory.name* field presents the following values:
{code:java}
    public static String UNDEFINED = "undefined";
    public static String TO_DO = "To Do";
    public static String IN_PROGRESS = "indeterminate";
    public static String COMPLETE = "Complete";{code}
We can further verify this by attempting to alter the filter. Only the 3 valid responses are available. 

!My Open Issues.png|width=566,height=162!
h3. Actual Results

Instead of returning the correct value in the filter, we get the erroneous statusCategory value of 'New'.

This is similar to the findings in JRACLOUD-68855.

The *status.statusCategory.name* will show incorrect values. From a preliminary analysis, it seems that this is occurring because the interface StatusCategory.java is referencing the following values:
{code:java}
    public static String UNDEFINED = "undefined";
    public static String TO_DO = "new";
    public static String IN_PROGRESS = "indeterminate";
    public static String COMPLETE = "done";{code}
Additionally, it appears this may present as the value is a [coded Constant|https://docs.atlassian.com/DAC/javadoc/jira/reference/com/atlassian/jira/issue/status/category/StatusCategory.html].

*_public static final String TO_DO_*
*_Constant Value: "new"_*
h3. Workaround

Currently, as a workaround you can manually alter the JQL after clicking the quick filter link in order to set the correct statusCategory. 

!Open Issues.png|width=1023,height=179!

h3. Issue Summary

Currently, the CSV export uses username information in user related fields (see [JRACLOUD-72088|https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-72088]).

When you remove an user, it turns it as an inactive user instantly, and its information will be converted to "removed..." in the database due to GDPR:
 !removedUser.png|thumbnail! 

Problem is that, even though you re-invite the same user (with the very same email address), Jira will map it back to the previous existing user, but the user related information will still be displayed as removed in the CSV export:
 !removedUser2.png|thumbnail! 


h3. Steps to Reproduce

* Invite a user (e.g. example@example.com);
* Set that user as assignee and/or reporter in an issue;
* Remove the user via site administration;
* Export that issue to CSV;
** User will be displayed as "removed...";
* Invite the user (very same email address) back;
* Export that same issue to CSV again.

h3. Expected Results

User related information will reflect the current active user.

h3. Actual Results

User related information will be displayed as "removed...".

h3. Workaround

None at the moment.

